00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:12.699
If you've ever done that, we'd like to expose that type of visual

00:17:12.699 --> 00:17:17.199
analysis visual display of complex values within within the data

00:17:17.199 --> 00:17:17.599
Explorer.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.800
Great, I think we have time for one more quick question.

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:25.900
Are there capabilities to explore data from relational databases

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:28.400
without having to load the tables into the environment?

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.099
Could you say that again?

00:17:30.099 --> 00:17:30.699
Sorry?

00:17:30.699 --> 00:17:34.599
Yeah, are there capabilities to explore data from relational databases

00:17:34.599 --> 00:17:36.900
without having to load the tables into the environment?

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:40.900
So we're we're planning to develop an integration between the data

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:43.000
Explorer and the connections pane.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:47.900
So if you're connected to a remote database Postgres database or

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:53.599
DuckDB database that you will be able to in in the future that you

00:17:53.599 --> 00:17:57.400
will be able to click on a table and get a data Explorer pane.

00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:01.599
There's some subtleties around we want to provide control to the

00:18:01.599 --> 00:18:06.500
user so that it does not execute too much unwanted computation so

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:10.300
you don't get a large bill from snowflake or from from your database

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:14.400
provider that you ran tons of queries because you just you clicked on

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:17.000
the wrong table and in the connections pane.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:22.300
So so probably some of the summary pane plots will be opt-in or like

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:26.800
click to compute so that we aren't spamming your snowflake warehouse

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:31.500
with too many too many potentially unwanted queries on a massive on

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:32.300
a massive table.

00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:36.099
I think this will go hand-in-hand with a sequel editing and

00:18:36.099 --> 00:18:40.300
development experience that we're planning to develop in positron in

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:41.199
the fullness of time.

00:18:41.199 --> 00:18:45.900
So I think that will all go hand-in-hand being able to develop and

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:49.400
test and run SQL queries directly within positron to see the outputs

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:53.500
of SQL queries within the data Explorer and to be able to see your

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:59.400
data warehouse as a as a pain in the connections pain in directly and

00:18:59.400 --> 00:19:00.300
directly in positron.

